Part a

Fit a multiple regression model to predict Sales using Price, Urban, and US.

model1_fit <- stats::lm(Sales ~ Price + Urban + US, data = car_seats)
base::summary(model1_fit)

Part b

Provide an interpretation of each coefficient in the model.

var_price <- if(stats::coef(model1_fit)[["Price"]] < 0) "drop" else "raise"
  • Price = -0.0544588 indicates that sales will drop, on average, by 54 units for every one dollar increase in their price (when holding Urban and US constant).
var_urbanyes <- if(stats::coef(model1_fit)[["UrbanYes"]] < 0) "lower" else "higher"
  • UrbanYes = -0.0219162 indicates that sales are, on average, 22 units lower for stores in urban areas, compared to stores in non-Urban areas (when holding Price and US constant).
var_usyes <- if(stats::coef(model1_fit)[["USYes"]] < 0) "lower" else "higher"
  • USYes = 1.2005727indicates that sales are, on average, 1201 units higher for stores in urban areas, compared to stores in non-Urban areas (when holding Price and Urban constant).

Part c

Write out the model in equation form, being careful to handle the qualitative variables properly.

\[Sales = 13.04 - 0.05 * Price - 0.02 * \text{I}_{(Urban = Yes)} + 1.2 * \text{I}_{(US = Yes)}\]

Part d

For which of the predictors can you reject the null hypothesis \(H_0: \beta_j = 0\)

Based on p-vales for Price and US.

Part e

On the basis of your response to the previous question, fit a smaller model that only uses the predictors for which there is evidence of association with the outcome.

model2_fit <- stats::lm(Sales ~ Price + US, data = car_seats)

Part f

How well do the models in (a) and (e) fit the data?

Based on \(RSE\) and \(R^2\), both models provide a good fit. Yet, the model from part e is preferable since it has a slightly lower \(RSE\) (2.469 for model e Vs. 2.472 for model a), and one less predictor.

Part h

Is there evidence of outliers or high leverage observations in the model from (e)?

model2_fit_diagnose <- lindia::gg_diagnose(
  fitted.lm = model2_fit,
  plot.all = FALSE
)
model2_fit_diagnose$res_fitted +
  ggplot2::geom_smooth(
    se = FALSE
  ) +
  ggplot2::theme(
    plot.background = ggplot2::element_rect(
      fill = "#F5F5F5",
      color = "#F5F5F5"
    )
  )

model2_fit_diagnose$scalelocation +
  ggplot2::labs(
    x = "Fitted Values",
    y = "sqrt(std res)"
  ) +
  ggplot2::theme(
    plot.background = ggplot2::element_rect(
      fill = "#F5F5F5",
      color = "#F5F5F5"
    )
  )

model2_fit_diagnose$qqplot +
  ggplot2::theme(
    plot.background = ggplot2::element_rect(
      fill = "#F5F5F5",
      color = "#F5F5F5"
    )
  )

model2_fit_diagnose$cooksd +
  ggplot2::theme(
    plot.background = ggplot2::element_rect(
      fill = "#F5F5F5",
      color = "#F5F5F5"
    )
  )

model2_fit_diagnose$resleverage +
  ggplot2::theme(
    plot.background = ggplot2::element_rect(
